
// Playwright AI Test Generation — Quiz (20 questions, GIFT, English)

::Q1: What are the three major stages of the AI test generation workflow?::
{
=Input → AI Generation → Output
~Requirements → Execution → Reporting
~Crawling → Parsing → Rendering
~Analysis → Deployment → Monitoring
}

::Q2: Which items are examples of AI generation INPUT sources?::
{
=User stories, HTML/DOM, POM, screenshots, OpenAPI specs
~Only screenshots and CSS files
~Only existing test files
~Only browser console logs
}

::Q3: Which part of the workflow performs prompt engineering and validation loops?::
{
=AI Generation stage
~Input stage
~Output stage
~Deployment stage
}

::Q4: What does AI generate well according to the document?::
{
=Boilerplate, CRUD tests, form validation, repetitive patterns
~Highly complex business rules
~Security penetration tests
~Performance threshold validations
}

::Q5: What does a user story–based generation typically produce?::
{
=A complete Playwright spec file with tests per acceptance criterion
~Only comments and TODO messages
~A list of CSS selectors
~A database schema
}

::Q6: Which locator rules are enforced in the SYSTEM_PROMPT for generating tests?::
{
=Use getByRole/getByLabel/getByTestId/getByText; avoid CSS and IDs unless allowed
~Use only CSS selectors
~Use XPath for all elements
~No restrictions are given
}

::Q7: What is a required naming convention for tests in generated specs?::
{
=should [expected behavior] when [condition]
~test_[scenario]_auto
~case-[number]
~scenario: [description]
}

::Q8: Which Playwright function must NEVER be used according to constraints?::
{
=page.waitForTimeout()
~page.locator()
~page.goto()
~expect.soft()
}

::Q9: Why is test.step() required for multi-step flows?::
{
=It improves readability and reporting for flows with 3+ actions
~It retries steps automatically
~It generates screenshots on each step
~It validates TypeScript types
}

::Q10: What does the data‑driven test generator create?::
{
=A loop generating multiple tests from a matrix of inputs
~A set of environment variables
~A JSON documentation file only
~A standalone fixture
}

::Q11: What is the AI-generated POM required to include?::
{
=Locators, actions, getters, navigation method
~Only actions, no locators
~Only locators, no methods
~Only constructor and URL property
}

::Q12: Which locator priority is enforced in POM generation rules?::
{
=getByRole > getByLabel > getByTestId > getByText > CSS
~CSS > getByText > getByRole
~XPath > CSS > getByRole
~All locators have equal priority
}

::Q13: What is forbidden when generating POM locators?::
{
=Using CSS class selectors and nth(0)
~Using getByRole
~Using page.locator at all
~Using testId attributes
}

::Q14: What does iterative refinement accomplish?::
{
=Allows multiple rounds of improving generated tests
~Automatically runs tests
~Guarantees 100% coverage
~Eliminates need for prompts
}

::Q15: What does the OpenAPI generator produce?::
{
=API tests for every endpoint and response code
~Only documentation of schemas
~Only POM classes
~Only authentication tests
}

::Q16: What can screenshot‑based generation provide?::
{
=Analysis of interactive elements, POM, and spec generation
~Only pixel‑diff tests
~Only accessibility reports
~Only CSS selectors for visible elements
}

::Q17: What is a required validation step for AI‑generated files?::
{
=TypeScript strict compilation (tsc --noEmit --strict)
~Manual code formatting
~Exporting screenshots to disk
~Running Lighthouse audits
}

::Q18: What does the static checker look for?::
{
=Anti‑patterns like waitForTimeout, nth(0), $, any
~Missing imports only
~Unused variables only
~Typos in comments
}

::Q19: What is the minimum AI review score recommended for approval?::
{
=7/10 or higher
~3/10 or higher
~10/10 only
~No minimum score required
}

::Q20: What does the full end‑to‑end pipeline generate?::
{
=A POM, spec files per story, and a validated test suite
~Only screenshots
~Only TypeScript interfaces
~Only JSON metadata
}

